{% block content %}
<header>
  <span class="icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-scroll"></i></span>
  <h1>History &amp; Origins</h1>
  <p>From a young man's prayer in a New York grove to a global church of over 17 million members — the story of how the Latter-day Saint movement began and grew.</p>
</header>

<main>

  <div class="intro-banner">
    <strong>A Restoration movement.</strong> The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints traces its origin to the early 1820s in upstate New York, during a period of intense religious revival known as the "Second Great Awakening." Its founder, Joseph Smith, taught that he was called to <em>restore</em> the original church of Jesus Christ rather than to reform an existing one.
  </div>

  <!-- The founding story -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-tree"></i> &nbsp;The Founding Story</div>

  <div class="narrative">
    <p><strong>The First Vision (1820).</strong> According to Joseph Smith's account, as a 14-year-old confused by competing religious revivals near his home in Palmyra, New York, he prayed in a grove of trees to ask which church he should join. He reported that God the Father and Jesus Christ appeared to him as two distinct, glorified beings and told him to join none of the existing churches. This event is foundational to LDS theology — it established, from the very beginning, the belief that the Father and the Son are separate physical beings.</p>
    <blockquote>"I saw two Personages, whose brightness and glory defy all description, standing above me in the air. One of them spake unto me, calling me by name, and said, pointing to the other — 'This is My Beloved Son. Hear Him!'" — Joseph Smith–History 1:17</blockquote>
    <p><strong>The Book of Mormon (1823–1830).</strong> Smith said that beginning in 1823, an angel named Moroni directed him to a set of golden plates buried in a hillside (the Hill Cumorah). He reported translating these plates "by the gift and power of God" into what was published in 1830 as the Book of Mormon — described as a record of ancient peoples in the Americas and their visitation by the resurrected Jesus Christ. Its stated purpose is to stand as "Another Testament of Jesus Christ" alongside the Bible.</p>
    <p><strong>Organization of the Church (1830).</strong> On April 6, 1830, Smith and a small group formally organized the Church of Christ (later renamed) in Fayette, New York, with six original members. They believed the priesthood authority to perform saving ordinances had been restored through angelic ministrations from John the Baptist and the ancient apostles Peter, James, and John.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Timeline -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-clock-rotate-left"></i> &nbsp;Timeline of Key Events</div>
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1805</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Joseph Smith is born</strong> in Sharon, Vermont, the fifth of eleven children in a farming family that later moved to Palmyra, New York.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1820</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>The First Vision.</strong> The 14-year-old Smith reports a vision of God the Father and Jesus Christ in a grove near his home — the founding theophany of the movement.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1830</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>The Book of Mormon is published</strong> in March, and the Church of Christ is organized on April 6 with six members.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1831–38</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Gathering to Ohio and Missouri.</strong> The growing church establishes communities in Kirtland, Ohio, and western Missouri. The first temple is dedicated in Kirtland in 1836. Conflict with neighbors intensifies.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1838–39</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>The Missouri "Mormon War" and Extermination Order.</strong> Governor Lilburn Boggs issues an order that Mormons must leave the state or be "exterminated." The Saints flee to Illinois.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1839–44</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Nauvoo, Illinois.</strong> The Saints build Nauvoo into one of Illinois's largest cities. Key temple doctrines (endowment, baptism for the dead, eternal marriage) are introduced. Plural marriage is privately practiced.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1844</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Joseph Smith is killed</strong> by a mob while jailed in Carthage, Illinois, at age 38. A succession crisis follows, splitting the movement into several branches.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1846–47</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>The Pioneer Trek West.</strong> Brigham Young leads the main body of Saints over 1,300 miles to the Salt Lake Valley, arriving July 24, 1847 — now celebrated as Pioneer Day.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1890</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>The Manifesto.</strong> President Wilford Woodruff issues an official declaration ending the practice of plural marriage, clearing the path for Utah statehood (granted 1896).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">1978</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Revelation on the Priesthood.</strong> President Spencer W. Kimball announces a revelation extending priesthood ordination and temple blessings to all worthy male members regardless of race, reversing a prior restriction on Black members.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">2018</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>Name emphasis.</strong> President Russell M. Nelson asks members and media to use the church's full name and to retire the nicknames "Mormon" and "LDS" in official contexts, reinforcing its Christ-centered identity.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-year">Today</div>
      <div class="tl-body"><strong>A global church.</strong> Over 17 million members worldwide across more than 160 countries, with 350+ operating or announced temples and a missionary force of roughly 60,000+.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Key figures -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-users"></i> &nbsp;Key Figures</div>
  <div class="figure-grid">
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Joseph Smith</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1805–1844 · Founding Prophet</span>
      <p>The founder and first president of the church. Reported the First Vision, translated the Book of Mormon, and introduced the temple ordinances. Killed by a mob in Carthage, Illinois.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Brigham Young</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1801–1877 · Second President</span>
      <p>Led the pioneer migration to Utah after Smith's death and is sometimes called the "American Moses." Oversaw the colonization of the Great Basin and founding of Salt Lake City.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Wilford Woodruff</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1807–1898 · Fourth President</span>
      <p>Issued the 1890 Manifesto officially ending plural marriage, a pivotal turn that enabled the church's accommodation with the United States and Utah statehood.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Spencer W. Kimball</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1895–1985 · Twelfth President</span>
      <p>Announced the 1978 revelation extending the priesthood to all worthy male members regardless of race, one of the most significant doctrinal developments of the 20th century.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Gordon B. Hinckley</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1910–2008 · Fifteenth President</span>
      <p>A public-facing leader who greatly expanded temple building and engaged extensively with national media, consistently affirming the church's Christian identity.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-card">
      <h3>Russell M. Nelson</h3>
      <span class="fc-dates">1924– · Seventeenth President</span>
      <p>A former heart surgeon who became church president in 2018. Emphasized using the church's full name and accelerated changes to worship and missionary programs.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Branches and offshoots -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-code-branch"></i> &nbsp;Branches of the Movement</div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p>After Joseph Smith's death in 1844, the movement he founded fractured over the question of succession. The great majority followed Brigham Young and the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles to Utah, becoming the church now headquartered in Salt Lake City.</p>
    <p>A significant minority did not. <strong>The Community of Christ</strong> (formerly the Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints, or RLDS), based in Independence, Missouri, followed Joseph Smith's lineal descendants and developed in a more mainstream-Protestant direction — it does not practice temple ordinances as the Utah church does and affirms a more traditional view of God.</p>
    <p>Smaller groups, often called <strong>Mormon fundamentalists</strong> (such as the FLDS), broke away later specifically to continue the practice of plural marriage after the main church abandoned it. These groups are not affiliated with and are formally disavowed by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.</p>
  </div>

</main>

